  "text": "To actually get to the element in the list, we need the graph to be represented as what is referred as adjacency array [CITATION_1] . Here given an index in the list of a vertex, we can access the (adjacent) vertex in that position of the vertex's adjacency list in constant time. Now if we simulate our rotate model algorithm of Theorem 1 in read-only memory using the auxiliary structure as stated in Lemma 6 as additional storage, then we obtain, Theorem 9. A DFS traversal of an undirected or a directed graph G, represented by an adjacency array, on n vertices and m edges can be performed in O(m + n) time using O(n lg(m/n)) bits, in the read-only model.",
